```class Solution {
public:
    int minimizeXor(int num1, int num2) {
        int x = num1;
        while (num2 != 0) {
            if ((num2 & 1) != 0) {
                x = x ^ num1;
            }
            num2 >>= 1;
        }
        return x;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(min(num1, num2)))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution uses a while loop to iterate until num2 becomes 0. Inside the loop, it checks the least significant bit of num2 using the bitwise AND operator (&) and XOR operation (^) with num1. This ensures that the number of set bits in x is the same as num2. Then, it shifts num2 right by one bit using the right shift operator (>>=) to reduce the number of bits processed in the next iteration. This approach has a time complexity of O(log(min(num1, num2)) due to the right shift operation, which reduces the number of bits processed in each iteration. The space complexity is O(1) since we only use a single variable (x) and no additional data structures. The energy implications are low because the algorithm operates on integers and performs bitwise operations, which generally consume less energy compared to other operations.

